==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pennant
<hw>Pen"nant</hw> <pr>(p⟦ecr⟧n"n⟦ait⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>penon</ets>, <ets>penoun</ets>, <ets>pynoun</ets>, OF.
<ets>penon</ets>, F. <ets>pennon</ets>, fr. L. <ets>penna</ets> feather.
See <er>Pen</er> a feather, and cf. <er>Pennon</er>,
<er>Pinion</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A small
flag; a pennon. The <stype>narrow pennant</stype>, <it>or</it>
<stype>long pennant</stype> (called also <xex>whip</xex> or <xex>coach
whip</xex>) is a long, narrow piece of bunting, carried at the masthead
of a government vessel in commission. The <stype>board pennant</stype>
is an oblong, nearly square flag, carried at the masthead of a
commodore's vessel.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧With flags and <xex>pennants</xex>
trimmed.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Drayton.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A rope or strap to
which a purchase is hooked.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

